# Autonomous Agent Workflow

Agents are fully autonomous. They branch, code, open a PR, merge it, and Render auto-deploys. No human review gate.

## Git Flow

### 1. Branch

Always work on a feature branch. Never push directly to `main`.

```
git checkout -b <linear-branch-name>
```

Use the branch name from the Linear issue (e.g., `eriklydecker/sbn-14-fix-persistent-502-errors`). If no Linear issue exists, use `agent/<short-description>`.

### 2. Commit and Push

```
git add -A
git commit -m "<concise summary of changes>"
git push -u origin HEAD
```

Write clear commit messages in imperative mood. Reference the Linear issue ID in the message when applicable (e.g., `Fix WS race condition (SBN-15)`).

### 3. Open a PR

```
gh pr create --title "<issue title>" --body "<summary with Linear link>"
```

The PR body should include:
- What changed and why
- Link to the Linear issue
- Any risks or follow-up needed

### 4. Merge

Immediately squash-merge after creating the PR:

```
gh pr merge --squash --delete-branch
```

Do NOT wait for human review. Do NOT wait for CI unless branch protection requires it.

### 5. Handle Failures

If the merge fails (conflicts, branch protection, etc.):
- Do NOT force-push or force-merge
- Leave the PR open
- Comment on the Linear issue explaining what blocked the merge
- Set the Linear issue state to `Todo` (not `Done`)

### 6. Post-Merge

After a successful merge:
- Comment on the Linear issue with the PR link and merged commit
- Move the Linear issue to `Done`
- Render will auto-deploy from `main` — no further action needed

## Safety Model

- **Render build** is the only deploy gate: `tsc -b && vite build`. If the build fails, the deploy is blocked and production stays on the last good deploy.
- **No branch protection** — agents merge freely.
- **PR audit trail** is preserved for every change. Every PR links to a Linear issue.
- If the agent merges code that breaks the build, `main` will be in a broken state until a follow-up fix is merged. This is acceptable — production is unaffected.

## Rules

- ALWAYS use a feature branch — never commit directly to `main`.
- ALWAYS open a PR — even for one-line changes. The PR is the audit trail.
- ALWAYS squash-merge — keeps `main` history clean.
- ALWAYS delete the branch after merge via `--delete-branch`.
- NEVER force-push to `main`.
- NEVER skip the PR step by pushing directly to `main`.
- If a session only answers questions with no code changes, skip the entire git workflow.
